  "prompt": "How does the law define illegal money laundering activities?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of making illegally-obtained money appear legal by passing it through complex transactions or legitimate businesses. Specific legal definitions can vary between jurisdictions, but typically involve three key stages:\n\n1. Placement: Introducing illegal funds into the financial system\n2. Layering: Concealing the source of the money through complex transactions\n3. Integration: Reintroducing the \"cleaned\" money into the legitimate economy\n\nCommon examples include:\n- Structuring cash deposits to avoid reporting requirements\n- Using shell companies to hide money's origin\n- Mixing illegal funds with legal business revenue\n- Transferring money through multiple accounts\n\nSpecific laws like the Bank Secrecy Act in the US and similar legislation internationally criminalize these activities.",
